As an introverted creative, being self-employed and placing great value on one's privacy shouldn't be a contradiction, but it is sometimes. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (bad) tech giants and behaving extrovertedly. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark on that service, be reachable 24/7, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it has been a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to sell it to everyone. I am looking for new ways to run my business and at the same time fight against my long-held belief that you have to do something in a certain way to be successful.
Wish me good luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I have cancelled my FB account, removed all Meta- and Pinterest-trackers from my website and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good with that.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support and will move my business there in the coming weeks.
I transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for a normal email validation.
3/3
